The paper focuses on understanding the effects of software development practices on the performance of developers working in stressful environments, which falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The use of non-invasive software measurement tools and biophysical sensors to collect data also suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and social computing (cs.SI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the identification of the best operating conditions for software development, which could fall under programming languages (cs.PL) and computer systems and networking (cs.CY) sub-categories.
